    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.25_0001"/>
                
                <figure>
                    <figDesc>A Rose</figDesc>
                </figure>
                
                <dateline>April 20, 1958</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Professor Neihardt,</salute>
                
                <p>I just want to add my sympathy to that of all who knew you and your wife. The first time I even met her &#8212; at a pre-meeting for the Missouri Writers' Workshop &#8212;
                
                    <fw type="curatorial">25</fw>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.25_0002a"/>
                    
                    it was clear that here was a person for whom Arnold's sweetness and light was an apt phrase, except that with rich electric warmth needed to be added. I suspect she left the same mark on everyone who knew her even slightly.</p>
                
                <p>I do pray for your faith and comfort in these sorrowful days. Your courage and lofty spirit have always
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.25_0002b"/>
                    
                    been so strong that we may hope for you joy in the future.</p>
                
                <p>It is a privilege to have known her even a little. With all sympathy,</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Katharine M. Gunnell</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <note type="curatorial"><hi rend="caps">JOHN G. NEIHARDT CENTER</hi></note>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
